A lot of you asked me to save this answer from my stories so I thought I’d make it into an IGTV post. I am answering one question everyday this month in honour of May being mental health awareness month. The question asked was: How can I be okay with my emotions and not feel overwhelmed by them? .

Also, in this video, I mention that we have the ability to control our emotions. But what I actually mean here is that we have the ability to control our *response* to our emotions. .

Hope some of you find this helpful ♥️ Take care, Nawal

node.title: How To Not Feel Overwhelmed by my Emotions

node.text:
Daily reminder: We do not have to like everyone and everyone doesn’t have to like us. If someone doesn’t like you even though you tried your best with them and had pure intentions, let it go. It’s not personal ♥️. This says a lot more about that person than it does about you. 

As a people pleaser and HSP, I learned this the hard way, but once I understood and believed this message - I’ve been liberated of the pressure to make everyone around me happy. I do the best with what I have and now it’s up to the other person to decide how they will take it.

What is an important lesson you learned that has changed how you see relationships? 

Take care of your mind and body. Love, Nawal ♥️

node.text:
As I start the series for Imposter syndrome, I wanted to first focus on where it stems from: low self esteem which makes us afraid of being discovered as incompetent. 

 Self esteem is depicted as a basic human motivation in Abraham Maslow's hierarchy of needs. He suggests that in order for an individual to grow and feel fulfilled, inner self-respect is required (i.e. self-esteem). 

Having healthy self-esteem is important because it can help you maintain a realistically positive attitude toward life and whatever it throws your way. It also influences your ability to accomplish your. goals and how you show up in relationships.

In my next few posts, I’ll be sharing some tips on how to combat low self-esteem and Imposter Syndrome. Follow along if you’re interested ♥️

node.text:
There is a lot of misconception about what mental health treatment looks like so I wanted to bring this post back up on the grid. Many believe we can only treat our mental health with medication and psychotherapy. Yes, these interventions are effective and preferred in severe cases of psychological distress. However, there are various other ways we can take care of our mental health (especially in the form of preventative measures from it becoming a mental health condition). 

If you have tried any of the above to improve your mental health (including medication and therapy), I’d love to learn about your experience in the comments below. I am sure there are many others who will benefit from it as well ♥️👇🏽

Note: I encourage you to use the information I share on here as a guide. Everyone’s experience is unique so some strategies/tools might not be relevant to your specific situation. Please see disclaimer in my highlights. Take care of your mind and body. Love, Nawal ♥️

In this post, Divya (@mindmatterswithdiv) and I share the 5 types of Imposter syndrome based on Dr. Valerie Young's research. They are categorized into:

1. The Perfectionist:
• Set unrealistic goals for themselves
• Become highly self-critical when they cannot achieve a goal
•Have difficulty delegating tasks to others (lack of trust in them getting things done the right way)

2. The Expert 
• Determine competency by how much they know or can do. 
• Often fear they don't know enough and will be considered inexperienced. 

3. The Superhuman
• Believe they got lucky with getting their job
• Often feel like a "fraud" around their colleagues 
• Work long hours (to the point of burnout) to prove their competency

4. The Natural Genius 
• Measure competency by how easily and fast they understand/do something
• Shame themselves if they are unable to do something quickly (e.g. on the first try) 

5. The Soloist 
• Tend to do everything on their own
• Refuse help as it makes them feel incompetent 

Have you experienced Imposter Syndrome? Which type do you see yourself in most?

Disorganized attachment style is also known as fearful avoidant. In adulthood, this attachment style leads to a fear of being hurt by those closest to them. This fear is a consequence of childhood trauma or abuse. When a child’s source of safety (i.e. caregivers) show highly inconsistent/contrasting behavior or abuse, it leads to a lack of trust in their relationships. Early on, these children realize that they cannot rely on those closest to them to support them or meet their needs. ⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
This attachment style is arguably the most difficult one to work through because it consists of both dismissive and anxious styles. Since there is a high likelihood of childhood trauma in individuals who identify with disorganized attachment style, I highly encourage to first start off by seeing a psychotherapist who can provide a supportive and non-judgmental space for you to work through and make sense of your experiences. In the meantime, it may also help to learn more about your attachment style and slowly work on trusting others while challenging the beliefs you hold about relationships in general.

Do you have a ‘Growth Mindset’?

In this post, Sophie (@sophiescott2) and I highlight the difference between a fixed and a growth mindset. 

This is a term developed by psychologist, Carol Dweck, from Stanford who was the first to explore the idea of fixed and growth mindsets.

If you believe your talents can be developed through hard work, good strategies and input from others, then you have a growth mindset.
Professor Dweck’s research found people who have a growth mindset are likely to achieve more than people with a fixed mindset who believe their talents are innate.

If you have a growth mindset, you are likely to seek help from others, try new strategies, and capitalize on setbacks to move forward effectively. 

It’s important to explore whether your mindset is fixed or not.
Having a growth mindset recognises that it takes commitment and learning from your mistakes to move forward.

What changes could you make towards developing a growth mindset?

Take care of your mind and body, Nawal♥️

Do you or someone you know have an avoidant attachment style? 

If you recognize you have a dismissive-avoidant attachment style, try to identify the behaviors you engage in that tend to sabotage your relationships and push people away. Understand that what you learned to survive as a child does not serve you anymore, so make an effort to slowly replace your avoidant behaviors with more genuine and connecting ones. It will feel uncomfortable at first so take small baby steps. 

Note: I encourage you to use the information I share on here as a guide. Everyone’s experience is unique so some strategies/tools might not be relevant to your specific situation. Please see disclaimer in my highlights. Take care of your mind and body. Love, Nawal ♥️

These are spot on! Thank you Najwa Zebian (@najwazebian) for your powerful words. 

The first one is a reminder I keep coming back to. It is so easy to blame others or our circumstance for our unhappiness. But in most cases, it is our mindset that needs to be shifted. Our mind creates our reality and our actions define it. Not realizing this can create many barriers in our mind that keep getting larger the more we maintain this fixed mindset. 

Which one of these do you resonate with? 

Btw Najwa Zebian recently published a book - Welcome Home. You can learn more about it on her IG ♥️ It is a gold mine of wisdom that speaks to the soul.

node.text:
Anxious attachment style usually develops when a parent (or primary caregiver) is unpredictable and does not provide adequate emotional care (i.e. shames/ridicules the child, puts too much pressure to be perfect)

This results in the child not knowing what response to expect and leaves them in chronic stress and fear. As a result, they become pre-occupied by how they are perceived and try to go above and beyond to seek positive validation from the parent/caregiver. 

 As adults, this might show up as feeling insecure about your relationship: overanalyzing your partner's behaviour and doubting whether your partner is committed to you. 

Other variables that account for development of insecure attachment are biological factors and previous traumatic relationship experiences.

Please keep in mind that insecure attachment styles are not a disorder. In fact, research shows 67% of adults have an insecure attachment. 

What is important is to recognize and understand your (or your partner's) attachment style and work towards developing secure attachment. 

Note: I encourage you to use the information I share on here as a guide. Everyone’s experience is unique so some strategies/tools might not be relevant to your specific situation. Please see disclaimer in my highlights. Take care of your mind and body. Love, Nawal ♥️

node.text:
5 Things You May Not Know Healthy Couples Do

1. They aren't always present in conversations (i.e. listening)

2. They sometimes fight and argue. Disagreements can happen

3. They don't always say the right thing, and may even hurt each others feelings sometimes

4. But they are always working toward improving their relationship. Improvement not Perfection 

5. They apologize when they mess up and are committed to resolving their issues

Healthy couples are not perfect. They don’t always do or say the right things, but they are dedicated to growing together and make an effort to keep working on their relationship. 

Glorifying healthy relationships as perfect can take a toll on our mental health as we may start to form unrealistic expectations.

Take care of your mind and body. Love, Nawal ♥️

node.text:
Since I have been discussing attachment styles, I wanted to shed some light on the role our parents/caregivers play on or attachment styles in adult relationships. 

If your primary caregiver was someone who was inconsistent with their emotional care, confusing or even frightening you at times, then you may have developed an insecure attachment style (anxious or avoidant types). You may have difficulty understanding your own emotions as an adult as well as other people’s feelings toward you. As such, you might struggle connecting with others - likely resulting in you either walking away from relationships prematurely or being too clingy/anxious in your relationships.

If you have an insecure attachment style, I want to emphasize that this can be unlearned. Now that you know better, you can work toward forming a more secure attachment style. I’ll share more on what that looks like in my next few posts. 

Take care of your mind and body. Love, Nawal ♥️

node.text:
Sometimes the assumptions we have about relationships can be misleading and lead to unnecessary resentment, guilt, or conflict. In this post, I wanted to highlight some things you might not know are completely normal in a healthy relationship. 

What are some assumptions you believed about relationships but now recognize they are not true/myths? 

I want to add that there is no strict rulebook for what a healthy and secure relationship looks like. We have guidelines and evidence-based research which are good to consider. However, you know your relationship better than anyone else and you get to decide how to ensure a mutually respectful and healthy bond between you and your partner. 

Note: I encourage you to use the information I share on here as a guide. Everyone’s experience is unique so some strategies/tools might not be relevant to your specific situation. Please see disclaimer in my highlights. Take care of your mind and body. Love, Nawal♥️
